Here's a typical registration setup:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — Singleton: one HttpClient/connection pool shared app-wide
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — Transient: fresh state each time a page is navigated to
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — Transient: new instance per navigation
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient` / shared state. One instance avoids socket exhaustion and lets you cache or queue requests. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should get a clean VM — no stale data from a previous visit. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Matches the VM lifetime; a new page binds to a new VM each time. |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** — stateless or intentionally shared state (HTTP clients, caches, logging).
- **Transient** — lightweight, stateful-per-use objects (VMs, pages).
- **Scoped** — rarely used in MAUI (no built-in request scope like ASP.NET). Avoid unless you create your own `IServiceScope`.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **Transient** or **Scoped** service into a **Singleton** — the shorter-lived service gets captured and effectively becomes a singleton too (the "captive dependency" problem).
